summary.para: Rounds a decimal using Math.Round, but adds the ability to 'stretch' a decimal to an x number of decimal positions.

para.example: For example, datatype decimal(18,4) from SQL comes into the application as 0.0000 and will be printed to 4 decimals even if the entire value is 0. Sometimes, for example for GPS coordinates, it is required to print the 0's behind a value. This is only possible for decimals, because they are fixed-precision numbers. However, the decimal needs to be stretched first if it has less precision than required.

member.param: The value to round.
The number of decimal positions, either more or less than the decimal currently has.
The rounding mode in case the decimal's precision is more than the provided number of decimal positions.
member.returns: The rounded (or stretched) decimal.

summary.para: A Thread Pool of which an instance can be created in order to split workloads into segments so that they don't interfere with each other. It can also be used to separate long-running or heavy work from the C# Thread Pool, which is not designed to handle this.

Please note that use of this Thread Pool works best if use of Tasks are avoided. If work is queued that uses Tasks to complete, it will switch to the C# Thread Pool as soon as the Task is encountered, simply because that is how Tasks work. Please be aware that this Thread Pool does not mix well with Tasks and asynchronicity. Since any work ran by this Thread Pool receives a dedicated thread, the queued work is best set up to be synchronous as much as possible or at least return to the same thread after asynchronous work has completed.

Please note that this ThreadPool has been tested, but may still contain some bugs. These bugs can be dependent on the type of work executed in this pool. For example, if too much work is queued that requires a connection to SQL, this work may fail on not being able to acquire a connection to SQL simply because there is too much work happening at once.
